04601nam a22006015i 9780804768344DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222007cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047683447 a10.1515/97808047683442doi  a(DE-B1597)581896  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aLAW0000002bisacsh00aLaw and Catastrophe /ced. by Austin Sarat, Lawrence Douglas, Martha Merrill Umphrey. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (184 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Amherst Series in Law, Jurisprudence, and Social Thought00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tContributors -- tA Jurisprudence of Catastrophe: An Introduction -- tCatastrophe: Flowing Up the Ground of Reason -- tCatastrophes and Humanitarian Corporate Responsibility: A Conceptual Critique -- tPolitical Catastrophe and Liberal Legal Desire: Two Stories of Revolution, Remediation, and Return from the French Nineteenth Century -- tCommitted to Memory: Rebecca West's Nuremberg -- tRAVIT PE'ER-LAMO REICHMAN -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe study of catastrophe is a growth industry. Today, cosmologists scan the heavens for asteroids of the kind that smashed into earth some ninety million years ago, leading to the swift extinction of the dinosaurs. Climatologists create elaborate models of the chaotic weather and vast flooding that will result from the continued buildup of greenhouse gases in the planet's atmosphere. Terrorist experts and homeland security consultants struggle to prepare for a wide range of possible biological, chemical, and radiological attacks: aerated small pox virus spread by a crop duster, botulism dumped into an urban reservoir, a dirty bomb detonated in a city center. Yet, strangely, law's role in the definition, identification, prevention, and amelioration of catastrophe has been largely neglected. The relationship between law and other limiting conditions—such as states of emergency—has been the subject of rich and growing literature. By contrast, little has been written about law and catastrophe. In devoting a volume to the subject, the essays' authors sketch the contours of a relatively fresh, yet crucial, terrain of inquiry. Law and Catastrophe begins the work of developing a jurisprudence of catastrophe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aLaw -- Jurisprudence. 4aLaw -- Law and Society. 4aSociology -- Social Movements, Civil Society, and Politics. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aDouglas, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouglas, Lawrence, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMeyer, Linda Ross, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReichman, Ravit Pe\x27er-Lamo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSarat, Austin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchafer, Sylvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShamir, Ronen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUmphrey, Martha Merrill, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYoung, James E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107042040 cprintz978080475683940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804768344?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804768344423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804768344/original  a978-3-11-070420-4  Stanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-d